Trivia
The news in Egg Inc contains many references to real life and various fictional universes.

Real Life
Elom Nusk is a reference to Elon Musk, founder of Tesla and SpaceX.
"SpaceEggs" is a pun on Elon Musk's SpaceX.
"Chicken-9" is a play on words for Space-X's rocket "Falcon 9".
"Teslegg" is a pun on Elon Musk's car company, Tesla.
"FedEggs" is a pun on FedEx.
"Mireggle gro" is a pun on the compost Miracle-Gro.
"One Small Step" is a reference to the famous speech Neil Armstrong made when he took the first steps on the moon in 1969.
The CRISPR Egg article named "Interstellegg" is a reference to the movie Interstellar.
'Rivihen' is a reference to the electric car company Rivian.
Star Trek
"Eggergize" is a pun on the common phrase "Energize" that is said by many Starfleet officers and personnel when teleporting or "beaming" to another location, and the Eggergize article describes this same function.
The "Prime Direggtive" is another pun on something from star trek, Mainly the "Prime Directive" A Directive that was put in place to stop Space-Faring Civilizations (Like Humans and Vulcans) from Interfering with the Evolution and Technological Advancements of More Primitive Civilizations.
The "Stranger Things" article mentions a "Federation of Planets," which may be a reference to Star Trek's government-like organization called The United Federation of Planets.
"Egggage" is a pun on a famous Star Trek catchphrase "Engage," commonly said when activating warp or engaging an enemy in battle.
The Graviton Drive is called a "Warp Drive" because that is what most FTL (Faster Than Light) Drives are called in Sci-Fi Media.
"Galactic Travelers" refers to the famous catchphrase of the Star Trek Series "To boldly go where no one has gone before"
Dilithium is used in Star Trek to power warp drives.
Other Media
The "Stranger Things" article name may be a reference to the TV show Stranger Things.
The Rocket Fuel Egg articles "To Infinity" and "And Beyond" are a reference to Buzz Lightyear's famous catchphrase "To Infinity And Beyond."
The Super Material Egg news articles have references to the properties of a fictional material called Transformium that was introduced in the live-action Transformers movie "Age of Extinction." The material is stated to be programmable and can change its shape, much like the Super Material Egg.
