Unlocking Spaceships
Upon acquiring Soul Eggs, and after having reached the Rocket Fuel Egg, an incomplete launch pad can be seen being built to the right of the Hatchery and Research Building. To finish its construction, two things must be reached: A laying rate of 100,000 Rocket Fuel Eggs per minute and 10,000 Soul Eggs. After the rocket pad has been constructed, players can then fund and fuel spaceships and send them on interstellar missions to find and retrieve Artifacts.

Funding a spaceship requires a specific amount of bocks. Once funded, the spaceship must be fuelled using a certain amount of eggs (later spaceships requiring multiple types of eggs) as a percentage of the farm's laying rate. Only one spaceship can be fuelled at a time, and players do not have to wait for the previously-launched spaceship to return before fuelling another. Three spaceship missions can be active simultaneously. Prior to Version 1.21, players with the Standard Permit only had one mission slot, and those with the Pro Permit had three. Additionally, the fuelling process of a spaceship can be aborted, losing all of its fuel. Spaceships cannot be aborted once launched.

Players start out with the Chicken One, and additional spaceships are unlocked after launching a set amount of the previous spaceship, as well as reaching certain Soul Egg threshholds.















Strategy
Send short length trips of the best rocket you can send. That is the fastest path to Atreggies Henliner, the last/best ship. On your journey to Atreggies Henliner, don't worry about crafting. Anything you can craft today will drop for free from the next ship. Most artifacts from lower ships will be comparatively useless in a month or so. Use what you have while you work your way up, but you're probably safe to consume most of the stuff you get. You should not, however, consume ingredients under any circumstance.

Spaceship statistics
A spaceship's capacity value displays the amount of items it will bring back, and the sensor level displays the approximate quality of the items. Spaceships launched outside of the Capacity Boost event will not have its capacity increased. Additionally, spaceships launched before upgrading the FTL Drive Upgrades or Zero-G Quantum Containment Epic Researches will have their duration and capacity unaffected.

A spaceship can have three different mission types, each affecting its capacity and the quality range of the items it brings back. These are short, standard, and extended.

In Version 1.21, stars were introduced to increase a spaceship's capacity and quality. Stars are obtained by gaining experience from launching spaceships, with each star requiring more experience than the last. The spaceship type affects the experience required per star and the maximum stars it can obtain, while mission type affects the experience gained per launch.

Quality
Ships have a quality range; provided you do not set a sensor target (which modifies the range downward, although the specifics are not understood; it appears that setting a target drops minimum quality to 0), this sets the minimum and maximum quality Artifacts, Eggfinity Stones, and Ingredients you can bring back. However, not all qualities are real; for example, there is no item with quality below 0.5. The formula for determining specific drop rates is not known, and it may be (and likely is) the case that quality ranges extending into nonexistent qualities helps with drop rates. Ships also have a "quality" of their own.

We have a heuristic formula for untargeted ship drop rates - this is usually but not always accurate. Here is the formula for dropping a given target:

