The most important takeaway here is that drops are inherently friendlier than crafting. An artifact's various rarities drop independently of each other, so unlike with crafting, where you are making 1 object which has a chance to be shiny, a ship capable of dropping an artifact will try to drop all of its rarities; what this does in practice is raise the odds of the artifact dropping at all based on the sum of its odds multipliers, so artifacts capable of multiple rarities tend to drop more often than their numbers would suggest if you thought of shipping as working like crafting does. Critically, due to this independence, ships can drop shinies at a greater than a 1 in 10 rate - again, unlike with crafting, where the chance to not be common caps at 10% and any potential shinies must contest that pool as you get better at crafting, that od value in the heuristic means all rarities have their drop chances modified appropriately. This modification is substantial, because the exponent - 9/10 or 8/10 - is equivalent to specific crafting experience in every artifact simultaneously (remember how that works: you have an exponent that is 1 at 0 previous crafts and .7 at 400 previous crafts). This means a Standard ship has an exponent equivalent to having crafted everything in the game 133.33 times (without any experience, i.e. at crafting level 1) and an Extended ship has an exponent equivalent to 266.67 previous crafts. Due to ship drop independence, extended ships are inherently better than you at producing any artifact with a crafting constant of about 17.78 or less, since they can get above 10% and you can't, on top of ships not needing any components (Golden Egg}}, ingredients, etc), just fuel and time. These reasons combined are why low-quality crafting is an inherently bad idea; you will generally waste resources you may want later for higher-quality crafting (or some other purpose, in the case of golden eggs) when you could just focus on sending ships and expect to drop the item faster than by crafting it. Crafting becomes important only when you reach artifact qualities so high that drop rates become very small or zero.

The second most important takeaway is that artifact explorer will give you potentially bad information if you are seeking rare drops and it recommends a standard or short ship, because artifact explorer sums drops across all rarities, and the longer your ship's duration, the more likely it is to drop rares over commons. An excellent example of this in practice is the T3L Ankh - at full stars, artifact explorer will tell you that you can get the most of these possible per day from a standard Henerprise and the second most per day from a short Henerprise (both targeting ankhs), but an extended Henliner targeting ankhs drops more rare and legendary ankhs per day than either of those ships, it just doesn't drop as many common ones.

Additional Notes:

Fragments and Stones count differently here.
Shininess of an artifact results in different odds multipliers but does not change quality.
Because in practice fragments and ingredients all have odds multipliers above 1 and artifacts and stones less than 1, extended ships have a reduced chance to bring in fragments and ingredients and an increased chance to bring in artifacts and stones.
qmax increases 5 times faster than qship as you gain stars, so the gap between them grows as well.
Ship Quality as it is used in the formula matches Ship Quality as it is listed in the game files, but the scaling does not. The rise in quality per star occurs at 1/5 the listed rate, so base quality numbers in the game's files (and shown below) are accurate, but scaled values are not.
Fuel Tank
Main article: Fuel Tank
In Version 1.21, the Fuel Tank was introduced, allowing players to fuel from that instead of from the farm. It has a base capacity of 2 billion and an output rate of 300 million per minute. Players can remove fuel from their Fuel Tank using the sliders. Simply drag the slider to where you want to dump the fuel, and tap 'remove' on the prompt that appears. This slider snaps to 1% increments.

The Fuel Tank has 7 upgrades, requiring the Pro Permit and Golden Eggs to upgrade. The upgrades cost a total of 15.3 million Golden Eggs, and the final upgrade increases the Fuel Tank's capacity and output rate to 500 trillion and 9 trillion per minute, respectively. The Fuel Tank's output rate is not affected by the Fuel Boost event.

List of Spaceships
Each spaceship after the Chicken One has a prerequisite of a certain number of launches of the previous ship, so the fastest way to unlock new spaceships is to stick to the "short" missions. For all spaceships, this is also the way to maximize how many items the spaceship will collect per unit of time, provided you are always ready to launch a new spaceship when one returns. Extended launches eventually take three or four different eggs as fuel, drastically increasing the time required to launch ships, owing to the need to change farms and the associated need to manually buy basic research all over again.

A fundamental concept inherent to spaceships is "quality" - how "good" its items are. Everything a spaceship can return with has an arbitrary quality value assigned to it which is not determinable by the player, and a spaceship only collects items within a given quality range. For the same spaceship, longer missions offer higher quality items. Note that the lowest quality items are quality 0.5, so as a practical matter, any quality below this is equivalent to 0.5.

Ships have star ratings, ranging from 0 (no stars) to a maximum amount varying by ship - the most, the Atreggies Henliner, can go up to 8 stars. Each additional star raises the capacity of all three runs you can make with the ship, by an amount that varies by both ship and run - the Extended Atreggies Henliner goes up the most, at +10 capacity per star, but all ships go up by at least +1 per star. Stars are collected by gathering enough launch points to pass a certain threshold which varies by ship; launch points are gathered by ship runs and vary by run but not by ship.

A short run generates 1 point, a standard run generates 1.4 points, and an extended run generates 1.8 points. This means for any given ship, you raise its star rating the fastest using short runs, provided you can fuel fast enough to keep up. It is not possible to directly see how many launch points you have or need in the game's interface - instead, when you are choosing a ship to fuel for a run, each ship has a circle drawn around it, showing your progress towards the next run.

Zero-G Quantum Containment applies after star ratings and is then floored. For example, an Extended Atreggies Henliner has a base capacity of 86; with 8 stars, this raises the capacity to 166. If you also have all 10 levels of Zero-G Quantum Containment, this is then increased by 50% to 249.

FTL Drive Upgrades applies to the Quintillion Chicken and above; these are also the only ships that can have a target set. While setting a target for a ship does increase its drop rate of the family you target (e.g. if you target shell stones, the sum of the drop rates of all tiers of shell stones will rise), the quality of the ship goes down, which can easily mean the drop rate of the highest tier of that family goes down. As a general rule, the only ship where you should seriously consider setting a target is on an 8-star (i.e. maxed out) Atreggies Henliner or Henerprise, unless you are replete with Golden Eggs and willing to craft what you need from lower-tier components. Even with an 8-star Atreggies Henliner, targeting can hurt you with certain hard-to-acquire items, but you should have been using artifact explorer for multiple months if you're at the point you're worried about targeting hurting you - the explorer is the best way to figure out what you should target and when.

