Trivia
On the Mission Control screen, the fueling progress bars for the currently funded ship are displayed in order from lowest to highest value egg, with an exception being that if you are on a farm with a valid fuel type then that egg's progress bar is larger and listed at the top.
If you are on a farm producing invalid fuel, the message "Current egg is not valid fuel" will be displayed.
If you are on a farm producing valid fuel (but that fuel has already reached its requirement and you still need other fuel before launching), the message "Current fuel type full, additional fuel required" will be displayed.
Only small egg icons are displayed on the default fueling screen. To see the name of the egg, tap on the rocket icon to the left of the screen.
Sometimes a later ship has lower capacity than an earlier ship, but the later ship has a higher quality to make up for it.
This happens for the first time with the upgrade from BCR to Quintillion Chicken.
It happens again when upgrading from Galeggtica to Defihent.
When you are launching your first two Chicken One rockets, you are presented with a screen that implies the options are only Demo and Standard (and Standard is shown as locked - so you cannot actually launch it). You can only see the Short and Extended mission types as options after you finish launching both Demo rockets, and you can then freely choose among Short, Standard, and Extended for all future launches.
Starting with Galeggtica, the ship will no longer fit on the fueling port. Instead, the spaceship will be in orbit while a smaller ship carries the crew.
The Galeggtica's fueling ship is similar in appearance to the Raptor spacecraft featured in the Battlestar Galactica, the TV series from which the Galeggtica was derived.
The fueling ship for the Defihent/Voyegger/Henerprise has a more aerodynamic design than the one used for the Galeggtica. This fuel ship is labeled "EGG-2802E", a reference to the Star Trek Enterprise ship registry number NCC-1701-D from The Next Generation upon which the Henerprise is based, with each nonzero digit increased by 1.
The Henerprise's sensor quality is named 'Next Generation'. This is a likely reference to the title of the aforementioned TV series.
In many cases, a previous ship's Extended Version brings higher quality artifacts than the current ship's Short version.
If a spaceship returns with an Artifact you've never had before, it will be labeled "NEW" on the collection screen.
An artifact of a new rarity (but the same type and tier as you've seen before) will not be marked "NEW".
Artifacts and Stones that are new will display a pop-up similar to one when crafting a new artifact.
Advanced Flow Control allows you to choose which percentage of eggs you'll divert toward fueling (as well as enable or disable the automatic stopping of fueling when upgrading eggs or prestiging). It is available as an option (below the "..." button to review the details of the ship currently being fueled) sometime after you unlock the Chicken Heavy Spaceship.
Only the two largest units of time remaining (days/hours, hours/mins, mins/secs) on each of your Spaceship missions will be displayed on the main screen of Mission Control. However, you can tap on the Spaceship in order to see more details (including the exact time remaining).
Note that an internet connection is required to collect rewards from spaceship missions. If you don't have a connection, you will get an error message when you try to collect, and you'll have to try again later once you are connected again.
This error also pops up when attempting to claim rewards after time cheating.
When a Contract awards Artifact boxes, the quality of the artifacts is based on the Standard length mission of the most advanced Spaceship you have unlocked. It uses the quality values from 0 stars of that ship.
Spaceship missions funded prior to Version 1.21 have a quality of 0 stars even after updating. The update only makes it so that newly funded missions have the appropriate star level (counting launches of that ship prior to the update).
Assuming the player always launches ships immediately after ships return, repeatedly launching Short missions will increase a ship's star level faster than repeatedly launching Standard and Extended missions.
For missions which only require 2 fuel types, there is a very simple fueling strategy for repeatedly launching them. Store fuel from one egg in your Fuel Tank and then build up a farm for the other egg. As your fuel tank depletes, refill it with eggs from the current farm. Then, when you can't launch any more ships, switch to the other farm. Repeat as many times as needed.
